"Yes, Captain. You should be on the move by now, they were still in the canteen, picking up their rations." At exactly 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We will be relocated to the advanced operational base I-131, fifty miles outside Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and later attack on Ianlos to drive out the rebels. There we will establish a base at the foot of the mountains", explained Shaw. "Departure to your squads and get on board."
The company broke up into their respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed to the tanks by the sergeants. Cohren boarded one of the tanks further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days ago, but knew little about them. He sat sideways and let his feet dangle, as he straightened his backpack and the radio set connected to his headset and laryngophone microphones.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?", asked Nemic, after they had settled in.
"You mean the rooster he stole?" Cohren recalled the morning when they took the animal with them on a farm. "Yes, I think so."
Cohren glanced over at one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his team. From the corner of his eye, he noticed the movement of a small hen, which was searching the surroundings by constantly turning its head.
“Yes, he's still with him,” Cohren replied as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
“All tanks are advancing,” the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the tank brigade and Strykers roared to life as they moved out. The Kronos tank, on which Cohren was riding, jolted as the brakes were released and they fell into formation. The tanks moved in a wedge-shaped formation over the Itania plain. Although the areas of marsh were frozen and the forests were covered in snow due to the winter storms, the mud was omnipresent.
About an hour later, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. “Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?”
“Yes, Operation Stormfire,” Cohren replied. “We thought it would be over in a few weeks, but we underestimated it.”
"‘Underestimated is strongly understated,' Nemic interjected into the conversation. 'We weren't prepared for their arsenal of weapons and the massive number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and the Erebus only last month. We should even have seen them on our way.'
"‘I stand firmly on the side of the Federation,' Orson said defiantly. 'I'm not going to let these terrorists scare me.'
"‘You're saying that now. But I've seen that most 18-year-old recruits like you will quickly take cover as soon as they hear a shot,' Craith explained.
"‘We'll see about that,' Cohren said laughing. Orson ended the conversation.'
"‘Exodus XO, Exodus CO,' Cohren's radio crackled. ‘We're receiving heat signatures, approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right.'
Cohren pulled up on the tank and put on his special glasses. As he switched them to "thermal imaging," he could recognize the signatures in the distance.
“Yes, I see them,” Cohren replied over his laryngophone.
“Are they hostile?” Natayla, the other recruit, asked.
“I cannot tell,” Cohren replied. He reached for his microphone and said: “Exodus Company, do not fire until under fire. Let's lure them out.”
As they drew closer, the point-like heat signatures took shape. As they got even closer, one of them ran hastily to get something and immediately returned to the small hill where the others were. The figures lay down on the ground, they took up firing position.
"We have enemy contact," Shaw called out over the radio as orange streaks from the hill were fired. While the tanks were under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket whizzed by and hit behind the formation in the ground, exploded, and scattered debris and rubble on one of the tanks. Another hit a Stryker APS-Cerberus sideways and exploded. The crew quickly got out and took cover as the ammunition flew into the air.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire at will," the commander of the tank platoon shouted over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew towards the hill and exploded, sending mud and stone into the air.
"Send in the Sentis," Knoxx called out, who was observing the hill with binoculars. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier came out, wearing a special headset. He gave orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Their thin, metallic arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted ahead. They carried their weapons on their backs.
"To kill or capture?" Craith asked, watching.
"Looks like a capture," Cohren guessed as the two Sentinels disappeared into the ash and smoke cloud. Shouts and shots echoed from the hill, but soon fell silent. Shortly afterwards, the two Sentinels returned and dragged someone behind them, whose boots left tracks in the ground. After returning to the safety of the train, they threw the figure to the ground. It groaned in pain as it landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw approached the figure that was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. „How many?“
„Three dead, sir“, replied the Sentinel. „The rest fled on foot.“
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. „Get rid of that guy for me!“
